{
  "doc_id": "11227",
  "text": "Habitual tea drinkers are reported to be at reduced risk of hip fractures and to have an increased bone mineral density. The main active compound of green tea is (-)-epigallocatechin gallate (EGCG), which can effectively scavenge ROS, such as superoxide anion radicals, hydrogen peroxide, hydroxyl radicals, peroxyl radicals, singlet oxygen, and peroxynitrite. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] EGCG can attenuate autoimmune arthritis by modulating Th17/Treg. [CITATION_3] EGCG can also ameliorate experimental arthritis, [CITATION_4] prevent osteoporosis in mice, and exert a therapeutic effect on periodontitis in rats. [CITATION_5] These effects may have a connection with blocking receptor activator of NF-κB ligand (RANKL)-induced nuclear factor kappa B (NF-κB), [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] the MAPK pathway, and proteasome-dependent degradation [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] in OC precursors. Moreover, EGCG has a wide range of pharmacological properties, including immunemodulating, anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, antioxidant, antimutagenic, and anticancer properties. [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] However, EGCG has several drawbacks for clinical applications due to its low aqueous solubility, which leads to poor bioavailability and adverse effects. [CITATION_15] In recent years, a number of researchers have shown that gold nanoparticles (GNPs) can be synthesized with drugs absorbed or conjugated onto the particle surface. [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] As nanocarriers, they have the advantages of low toxicity, easy synthesis, large surface area, excess loading of pharmaceuticals, and enhanced permeability and retention effect. [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] Wang et al conjugated doxorubicin onto the surface of GNPs with a poly(ethylene glycol) spacer via an acid-labile linkage, which can release doxorubicin in response to the pH of acidic organelles following endocytosis to achieve enhanced drug accumulation and retention in multidrug-resistant cancer cells. [CITATION_21] Conners et al utilized bisphosphonate-functionalized GNP to treat osteoporotic bone diseases. [CITATION_22] Moreover, Sul et al demonstrated that GNPs inhibited RANKL and reduced ROS levels in BMMs. [CITATION_23] GNPs have shown favorable bioavailability and promising advantages as nanocarriers for drug delivery. [CITATION_24] [CITATION_25] Tea catechins have been reported to augment the cellular uptake of nanoparticles.",
